  <section xml:id="Quiz_4">
        <title>Quiz 4</title>
<subsection xml:id="Quiz_4_Solutions">
    <title>Question 1</title>

    <p> The idea is to use the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic.
        Since <m>p|a^n</m>, <m>p|a.</m> 
        
    </p>
    
    <p>(This follows from Corollary 1 to Theorem 3.1.   You don't need to be able to cite the Theorem/Corollary.) </p>
        

    <p>

        Thus, we can write <m>a</m> as
        <md>
            a=p\cdot p_1^{e_1}p_s^{e_2}\cdots p_t^{e_t}
        </md>
    </p>
        <p>(alterntively you could simply write <m>a=p\cdot w</m>)</p>
            
        <p>

        Then <md>
            a^n=p^n\cdot p_1^{ne_1}p_s^{ne_2}\cdots p_t^{ne_t}
        </md>

        and hence <m>p^n|a^n.</m>
    </p>

    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="Quiz_4_2">
    <title>Question 2</title>
    <p>
        Counter-example: <m>12|6^2</m>, <m>12^2 \nmid 6^2</m>
    </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="Quiz_4_3">
    <title>Question 3</title>

    <p>
        
   
 For all integers <m>n>1</m>, <m>n!</m> is even. So <m>n!+1</m> is odd and all its prime divisors must also be odd.   Let <m>p</m> be any prime divisor of <m>n!+1.</m> Suppose <m>p \leq n.</m> Then <m>p|n!</m> and so <m>p|(n!+1)-(n!)</m>. That is, <m>p|1</m>  which is impossible.
 </p>
</subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="Quiz_4_4">
    <title>Question 4</title>

    <p>
        
 The difference of two odd integers is even.  So,  
if <m>p-q=3</m> then <m>q=2.</m>  (Clearly <m>2-q=3</m> won't work.) Then <md>
    <mrow>p-2 \amp = 3 </mrow>
    <mrow>p \amp =5 </mrow>
</md>

 </p>
</subsection>
</section>
        